<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-101-390  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 101 390.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Dec 18 1989 v3 n51 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>OMB guts funding for NCIC. (the Office of Management and Budgetcuts the FBI's budget request for the National Crime InformationCenter 2000 program)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rivenbark, Leigh.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Office of Management and Budget (OMB) cuts the FBI's 1991budget request for the National Crime Information Center (NCIC)2000 program.andP;  The move was made in the spirit of the Gramm-RudmanAct, which frowns on any new programs, rather than for reasonshaving to do with the system itself, according to Congressionalsources.andP;  NCIC answers 750,000 queries a day from federal, stateand local law enforcement officials over dedicated communicationslines; it also stores 20 million records on wanted or missingpersons and stolen property.andP;  The FBI requested $17 million todevelop NCIC 2000 and estimated that the entire program would cost$75 million over six years.andP;  The new system would have improveddata search speeds and would include a relational DBMS, imagetransmission, intelligent terminals, an enhanced communicationsnetwork and connections to its Canadian counterpart.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Law EnforcementData BasesTelecommunicationsNetwork ManagementGovernment AgencyConnectivityPlanningEnhancementsBudgetingUnited States. Office of Management and BudgetUnited States. Federal Bureau of InvestigationUnited States. National Crime Information Center.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>